Part I - Loan Data Exploration¶

by Javier Martínez¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing loans (extracted from Prosper, America's first peer-to-peer lending marketplace, with over $7 billion in funded loans) with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income and many others.

    'LoanStatus': [
        'Current',
        'Completed',
        'Chargedoff',
        'Defaulted',
        'Past Due (1-15 days)',
        'Past Due (31-60 days)',
        'Past Due (61-90 days)',
        'Past Due (91-120 days)',
        'Past Due (16-30 days)',
        'FinalPaymentInProgress',
        'Past Due (>120 days)',
        'Cancelled'
    ],
    'Term': [
        36,
        60,
        12
    ],
    'EmploymentStatus': [
        'Employed',
        'Full-time',
        'Self-employed',
        'Not available',
        'Other',
        'Part-time',
        'Not employed',
        'Retired'
    ],
    'ProsperRating': ['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR']
}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(
        ordered = True,
        categories = ordinal_var_dict[var]
    )
    df[var] = df[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset consists of 113,937 loan records with 81 features. This data dictionary explains variables.

For this project, a second data set has been formed based on the original with 13 features on which the Exploration Data Analisys (EDA) will focus.

Column Description
ListingKey Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.
LoanOriginalAmount The origination amount of the loan.
Term The length of the loan expressed in months.
BorrowerAPR The borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
BorrowerRate The borrower's interest rate for this loan.
ProsperRating Allow potential investors to easily consider a loan application's level of risk because the rating represents an estimated average annualized loss rate range to the investor.
[AA, A, B, C, D, E, HR]
EstimatedReturn The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created. Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
MonthlyLoanPayment The scheduled monthly loan payment.
EmploymentStatus The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
IncomeRange The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
StatedMonthlyIncome The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
LoanStatus The current status of the loan:
[Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue]
(The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket)
ListingCategory The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing:
[0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7 - Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans]

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Firstly, I am interested in identifying what affects the borrower's APR or interest rate, one of the most important parameters when applying for a loan. Then, what are the differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount is. Finally, what factors affect a loan’s status.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I have created a dataset with some features that I think will be helpful in the research: the borrower's interest rate (BorrowerRate) and the assigned Prosper rating (ProsperRating - Alpha) will affect the Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (BorrowerAPR) for the loan, as these parameters are used to calculate this last value, and will also set the estimated return (EstimatedReturn). The original loan amount (LoanOriginalAmount) is likely to vary depending on its use (ListingCategory) and the current status (LoanStatus) could depend on the length, in months, (Term) and the monthly payment (MonthlyLoanPayment), which in turn will depend on the borrower's employment status when applying for the loan (EmploymentStatus) and the borrower's income range, annually (IncomeRange) and monthly (StatedMonthlyIncome). All these data can help to draw conclusions about the main features of interest in the dataset.

Univariate Exploration¶

I will start by taking a look at the distribution of one of the main variables of interest: Borrower's APR

Following the definitions from Bank of America:

  • APR (BorrowerAPR) is the annual cost of a loan to a borrower — including fees. Unlike an interest rate, however, it includes other charges or fees such as mortgage insurance, most closing costs, discount points and loan origination fees.
  • Interest rate (BorrowerRate) refers to the annual cost of a loan to a borrower.

This means that the distribution of BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate should be similar with slight difference since the APR is always higher than the interest rate.

I'll now look at the other features in the data to see if any of them hold interesting properties.

What about loan ratings? Prosper ratings allow potential investors to easily consider a loan application's level of risk because the rating represents an estimated average annualized loss rate range to the investor. This rating is a system patented by the company to maintain consistency in the evaluation of the loan.

Following this link explains the percentages for the Annual Loss Rate. Two scores are used to calculate this value: the borrower's credit score (CreditGrade), obtained from an official credit reporting agency, and the Prosper score (ProsperScore), figured in-house based on the Prosper population.

Therefore, in order to obtain meaningful conclusions, only the resulting final value that is useful to the investor is observed, that is, 'ProsperRating' column.

By a large margin, more than 50.000 (62.5%) of the loans granted are for the purpose of debt consolidation. Debt consolidation is a form of debt refinancing that involves taking out one loan to pay off many others. Although the original dataset offers the option to investigate whether borrowers have other loans granted with the same company (TotalProsperLoans), this variable is not considered to be of interest as users may have other types of debts. Other notable uses are 'Home Improvement', 'Business' and 'Auto'. Category "Other" could indicate that there are many other types of use that have not been recorded and have been classified in this group.

In any case, these data indicate that this variable is not significant to set differences according to the amount of the loan.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of the Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan looks multimodal. For the loan orignal amount there are several peaks centered at \$4,000, \\$10,000, \$15,000, \\$20,000 and \$25,000.

Unusual points were found and eliminated in the stated monthly income variable. No need to perform any transformations on these three variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Duplicate loan records and numeric values with missing information have been removed.

Some column values have been converted to categorical types.

For the 'LoanStatus' column, the 'Pas Due' type categories have been merged into one, since it is not a value of interest for the investigation. The same goes for some categories in the "IncomeRange" and "EmploymentStatus" columns.

When investigating stated monthly income, a number of outlier points were identified. Overall, these points could be characterized by an inconsistency between the recorded value and the other features. For security, all of these points were removed from the dataset in order to move forward.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The original loan amount has a positive linear relationship with the monthly payment variable, the borrower's monthly income range and the length of the loan. However, it is negatively correlated with the borrower's annual percentage rate and the borrower's interest rate.

The borrower's annual percentage rate and the borrower's interest rate are two closely related values and, together with the estimated return, are used by Prosper to assign a rating to the loan which helps potential investors to easily consider the risk level of a loan application.

Regarding the status of the loan, the percentage of loans that are currently being paid or have already been completed is very high, with the status of the remaining loans being very insignificant. In general, loans already paid correspond to small amounts of money.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Expected relationships were found in the association between the monthly loan payment and the stated monthly income and between the rating assigned by the company and the estimated return for the loan.

Conclusions¶

In the course of this research, the relationships between some of the most important parameters when applying for a loan have been explored.

What affects the Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) or the borrower's interest rate? Both parameters have a very similar distribution, with a slight difference in that the APR value is always higher than the interest rate because it includes fees. There are several parameters in the dataset that are related to these two values. The first is the original loan amount. The higher this amount, the smaller the borrower's annual percentage rate for the loan. The second parameter is the Prosper rating, a rating given by the company. Generally speaking, loans with a very small Annual Loss Rate ('A', 'B', 'C') have a small APR value, while those rated as high risk ('D', 'E', 'HR') have a high APR value. The third and last value is the estimated return, which is strongly positively correlated.

What are the differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount is ? There are certain features that differentiate loans according to the original loan amount. Generally, as the loan amount increases, so does the length of the loan, i.e. larger loans are granted for 60 months. The borrower's annual percentage rate (APR) and the borrower's interest rate for this loan are inversely proportional to the loan amount. This means that smaller loan amounts will have higher interest rates and vice versa. In turn, these two pieces of information are used to calculate the monthly payment amount, which also increases as the loan amount increases. The borrower's annual income range is positively related to the original loan amount, which means that loans are not granted beyond the borrower's financial means. Finally, the purpose or reason for applying for these loans did not prove to be a differentiating element as a very significant percentage of these loans (76.8%) were granted for debt consolidation, home improvement or business purposes.

For all loans contained in the dataset, 89.8% of the loans granted are in the process of being repaid or have already been completed. The most significant difference was found in the original loan amount, the smallest loans usually having already been repaid. No other factors affecting the status of the loan have been observed.
